#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:1
msgid "Issue triage"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:3
msgid ""
"Currently, _Black_ uses the issue tracker for bugs, feature requests, "
"proposed style modifications, and general user support. Each of these issues "
"have to be triaged so they can be eventually be resolved somehow. This "
"document outlines the triaging process and also the current guidelines and "
"recommendations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:9
msgid ""
"If you're looking for a way to contribute without submitting patches, this "
"might be the area for you. Since _Black_ is a popular project, its issue "
"tracker is quite busy and always needs more attention than is available. "
"While triage isn't the most glamorous or technically challenging form of "
"contribution, it's still important. For example, we would love to know "
"whether that old bug report is still reproducible!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:15
msgid ""
"You can get easily started by reading over this document and then responding "
"to issues."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:17
msgid ""
"If you contribute enough and have stayed for long enough, you may even be "
"given Triage permissions!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:21
msgid "The basics"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:23
msgid ""
"_Black_ gets a whole bunch of different issues, they range from bug reports "
"to user support issues. To triage is to identify, organize, and kickstart "
"the issue's journey through its lifecycle to resolution."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:27
msgid "More specifically, to triage an issue means to:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:29
msgid "identify what type and categories the issue falls under"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:30
msgid "confirm bugs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:31
msgid "ask questions / for further information if necessary"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:32
msgid "link related issues"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:33
msgid "provide the first initial feedback / support"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:35
msgid ""
"Note that triage is typically the first response to an issue, so don't fret "
"if the issue doesn't make much progress after initial triage. The main goal "
"of triaging to prepare the issue for future more specific development or "
"discussion, so _eventually_ it will be resolved."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:40
msgid ""
"The lifecycle of a bug report or user support issue typically goes something "
"like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:42
#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:59
msgid "_the issue is waiting for triage_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:43
msgid ""
"**identified** - has been marked with a type label and other relevant "
"labels, more details or a functional reproduction may be still needed (and "
"therefore should be marked with `S: needs repro` or `S: awaiting response`)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:46
msgid ""
"**confirmed** - the issue can reproduced and necessary details have been "
"provided"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:47
msgid ""
"**discussion** - initial triage has been done and now the general details on "
"how the issue should be best resolved are being hashed out"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:49
msgid ""
"**awaiting fix** - no further discussion on the issue is necessary and a "
"resolving PR is the next step"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:51
msgid "**closed** - the issue has been resolved, reasons include:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:52
msgid "the issue couldn't be reproduced"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:53
msgid "the issue has been fixed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:54
msgid "duplicate of another pre-existing issue or is invalid"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:56
msgid ""
"For enhancement, documentation, and style issues, the lifecycle looks very "
"similar but the details are different:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:60
msgid ""
"**identified** - has been marked with a type label and other relevant labels"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:61
msgid ""
"**discussion** - the merits of the suggested changes are currently being "
"discussed, a PR would be acceptable but would be at significant risk of "
"being rejected"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:63
msgid ""
"**accepted & awaiting PR** - it's been determined the suggested changes are "
"OK and a PR would be welcomed (`S: accepted`)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:65
msgid "**closed**: - the issue has been resolved, reasons include:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:66
msgid "the suggested changes were implemented"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:67
msgid "it was rejected (due to technical concerns, ethos conflicts, etc.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:68
msgid "duplicate of a pre-existing issue or is invalid"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:70
msgid ""
"**Note**: documentation issues don't use the `S: accepted` label currently "
"since they're less likely to be rejected."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:73
msgid "Labelling"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:75
msgid ""
"We use labels to organize, track progress, and help effectively divvy up "
"work."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:77
msgid ""
"Our labels are divided up into several groups identified by their prefix:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:79
msgid "**T - Type**: the general flavor of issue / PR"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:80
msgid ""
"**C - Category**: areas of concerns, ranges from bug types to project "
"maintenance"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:81
msgid "**F - Formatting Area**: like C but for formatting specifically"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:82
msgid "**S - Status**: what stage of resolution is this issue currently in?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:83
msgid "**R - Resolution**: how / why was the issue / PR resolved?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:85
msgid "We also have a few standalone labels:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:87
msgid ""
"**`good first issue`**: issues that are beginner-friendly (and will show up "
"in GitHub banners for first-time visitors to the repository)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:89
msgid ""
"**`help wanted`**: complex issues that need and are looking for a fair bit "
"of work as to progress (will also show up in various GitHub pages)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:91
msgid ""
"**`ci: skip news`**: for PRs that are trivial and don't need a CHANGELOG "
"entry (and skips the CHANGELOG entry check)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:93
msgid ""
"**`ci: build all wheels`**: when a full wheel build is needed, such as to "
"debug platform-specific issues. Black does not build wheels for every "
"platform on each pull request because the full build matrix is expensive. "
"After the label is added, the workflow starts only when a new commit is "
"pushed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:99
msgid ""
"We do use labels for PRs, in particular the `ci: skip news` label, but we "
"aren't that rigorous about it. Just follow your judgement on what labels "
"make sense for the specific PR (if any even make sense)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:104
msgid "Projects"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:106
msgid ""
"For more general and broad goals we use projects to track work. Some may be "
"long-term projects with no true end (e.g. the \"Amazing documentation\" "
"project) while others may be more focused and have a definite end (like the "
"\"Getting to beta\" project)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:111
msgid ""
"To modify GitHub Projects you need the [Write repository permission level or "
"higher](https://docs.github.com/en/organizations/managing-access-to-your-"
"organizations-repositories/repository-permission-levels-for-an-"
"organization#repository-access-for-each-permission-level)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:115
msgid "Closing issues"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:117
msgid ""
"Closing an issue signifies the issue has reached the end of its life, so "
"closing issues should be taken with care. The following is the general "
"recommendation for each type of issue. Note that these are only guidelines "
"and if your judgement says something else it's totally cool to go with it "
"instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:122
msgid ""
"For most issues, closing the issue manually or automatically after a "
"resolving PR is ideal. For bug reports specifically, if the bug has already "
"been fixed, try to check in with the issue opener that their specific case "
"has been resolved before closing. Note that we close issues as soon as "
"they're fixed in the `main` branch. This doesn't necessarily mean they've "
"been released yet."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:128
msgid ""
"Design and enhancement issues should be also closed when it's clear the "
"proposed change won't be implemented, whether that has been determined after "
"a lot of discussion or just simply goes against _Black_'s ethos. If such an "
"issue turns heated, closing and locking is acceptable if it's severe enough "
"(although checking in with the core team is probably a good idea)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:134
msgid ""
"User support issues are best closed by the author or when it's clear the "
"issue has been resolved in some sort of manner."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:137
msgid ""
"Duplicates and invalid issues should always be closed since they serve no "
"purpose and add noise to an already busy issue tracker. Although be careful "
"to make sure it's truly a duplicate and not just very similar before "
"labelling and closing an issue as duplicate."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:142
msgid "Common reports"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:144
msgid ""
"Some issues are frequently opened, like issues about _Black_ formatted code "
"causing E203 messages. Even though these issues are probably heavily "
"duplicated, they still require triage sucking up valuable time from other "
"things (although they usually skip most of their lifecycle since they're "
"closed on triage)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:149
msgid ""
"Here's some of the most common issues and also pre-made responses you can "
"use:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:151
msgid "\"The trailing comma isn't being removed by Black!\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:153
msgid ""
"Black used to remove the trailing comma if the expression fits in a single "
"line, but this was changed by #826 and #1288. Now a trailing comma tells "
"Black to always explode the expression. This change was made mostly for the "
"cases where you _know_ a collection or whatever will grow in the future. "
"Having it always exploded as one element per line reduces diff noise when "
"adding elements. Before the \"magic trailing comma\" feature, you couldn't "
"anticipate a collection's growth reliably since collections that fitted in "
"one line were ruthlessly collapsed regardless of your intentions. One of "
"Black's goals is reducing diff noise, so this was a good pragmatic change.\n"
"\n"
"So no, this is not a bug, but an intended feature. Anyway, [here's the "
"documentation](https://github.com/psf/black/blob/master/docs/"
"the_black_code_style.md#the-magic-trailing-comma) on the \"magic trailing "
"comma\", including the ability to skip this functionality with the `--skip-"
"magic-trailing-comma` option. Hopefully that helps solve the possible "
"confusion.\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:159
msgid "\"Black formatted code is violating Flake8's E203!\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing/issue_triage.md:161
msgid ""
"Hi,\n"
"\n"
"This is expected behaviour, please see the documentation regarding this case "
"(emphasis mine):\n"
"\n"
"> PEP 8 recommends to treat : in slices as a binary operator with the lowest "
"priority, and to leave an equal amount of space on either side, **except if "
"a parameter is omitted (e.g. ham[1 + 1 :])**. It recommends no spaces "
"around : operators for “simple expressions” (ham[lower:upper]), and **extra "
"space for “complex expressions” (ham[lower : upper + offset])**. **Black "
"treats anything more than variable names as “complex” (ham[lower : upper + "
"1]).** It also states that for extended slices, both : operators have to "
"have the same amount of spacing, except if a parameter is omitted (ham[1 + "
"1 ::]). Black enforces these rules consistently.\n"
"\n"
"> This behaviour may raise E203 whitespace before ':' warnings in style "
"guide enforcement tools like Flake8. **Since E203 is not PEP 8 compliant, "
"you should tell Flake8 to ignore these warnings**.\n"
"\n"
"https://black.readthedocs.io/en/stable/the_black_code_style/current_style."
"html#slices\n"
"\n"
"Have a good day!\n"
msgstr ""
